Operators apply operations to one or more operands.
When an expression contains several operators, they get
applied in order of their precedence, highest to
lowest. When equal, associativity decides. When
parsing, compound expressions are seen as rooted trees,
where internal nodes are operators, and the leaf nodes
are atomic expressions. When building this tree, we
informally say that higher precedence "binds tighter".
